{{Infobox stadium | name = Olympia-Kunsteisstadion | nickname = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = | caption = | fullname = | former_names = | location = {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]], [[Germany]] | coordinates = {{Coord|47|29|20|N|11|5|44|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = 106 days | opened = {{Start date|1934|12|16}} | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = | embedded = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
The '''Olympia-Kunsteisstadion''' is a [[Ice skating|skating]] [[stadium]] located in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]].
It was built according to plans of architect [[Hanns Ostler]] in only 106 days for the [[figure skating at the 1936 Winter Olympics|figure skating]] and [[ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics|ice hockey]] at the [[1936 Winter Olympics]]. It was opened on 16 December 1934. It contained an ice rink 30 meters by 60 meters for these games. It was a partially covered stadium. The stadium was able to hold 10,000 people.
The Olympia-Kunsteistadion was rebuilt in 1939/1940 for the planned [[1940 Winter Olympics]] which were canceled due to [[World War II]].
After the war it was reopened in 1948. the stadium received a complete roof in 1964. From 1990 to 1994 it was rebuilt again and is now the Olympic-Eissport-Zentrum of Garmisch-Partenkirchen.
