'''Walhalla Idrottsplats''' (short form '''Walhalla IP''') was a sports [[stadium]] in [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]] with a total capacity of 8,000. It was located near [[Korsvägen]], on the site that currently is the [[Swedish Exhibition and Congress Centre]]. Walhalla IP was in use between 1908 and 1921.

== History ==

Walhalla IP was built by [[Örgryte IS]] in 1908 to replace their old stadium [[Balders Hage]] as the [[Swedish Football Association]] had banned international football on it.{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}} The city deeded land to Örgryte IS for this purpose, which today is used by the Swedish Exhibition and Congress Centre, opposite to amusement park [[Liseberg]].{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}}{{sfn|IFK Göteborg – Arenor genom åren}}

The roofed main stand had 1,200 seats, and another 6,800 spectators could be accommodated on terraces around the pitch. The stadium was modelled after [[Liverpool F.C.]]'s [[Anfield]].{{sfn|Persson|2011|p=131}} At the time of its opening, Walhalla IP was the most modern stadium in [[Scandinavia]].{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}} The pitch was enclosed by a slightly longer than 400 metre [[All-weather running track|running track]] and other [[sport of athletics|athletics]] facilities,{{sfn|Persson|2011|p=131}} and several Swedish athletics championships were held in the stadium.{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}}

The inauguration match was played on 6 September 1908, between Örgryte and German champions [[BFC Viktoria 1889|Viktoria Berlin]].{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}} It was the main venue for sports events in Sweden until [[Stockholm Olympic Stadium]] was opened in 1912. The [[Sweden national football team|Swedish national team]] played its first ever international against [[England national football team]] on Walhalla IP in September 1908,{{sfn|Persson|2011|p=133}} and [[IFK Göteborg]]—that rented the stadium from Örgryte IS—won their two first [[List of Swedish football champions|Swedish championships]], in 1908 and 1910, there.{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}}

In 1912, the stadium was the scene of one of the first known instances of Swedish [[football hooliganism]]. IFK Göteborg supporters [[pitch invasion|stormed the pitch]] to get to the referee, who had first awarded IFK a penalty kick against Örgryte IS in the last minute of the match, but then blown the final whistle before the kick could be taken.{{sfn|Persson|2011|pp=225–227}}

IFK Göteborg left Walhalla IP for newly built [[Gamla Ullevi (1916)|Ullevi]] in 1916.{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}} The land on which Walhalla IP stood was chosen as one of the sites for the 1923 [[Gothenburg Exhibition (1923)|Gothenburg Tercentennial Jubilee Exposition]], and Örgryte IS was forced to move from the stadium as a consequence.{{sfn|Josephson|Jönsson|2004|p=44}}{{sfn|Alsiö|Persson|2011}} The last event at Walhalla was an international sports gala arranged by Örgryte and held on 25 September 1921.{{sfn|Jerneryd|1981|p=96}}

